Learning Objectives
At the end of this part, readers will be able to:

Define uncertainty quantification;
Distinguish between the methods and assumptions for parametric, semi-parametric, and non-parametric approaches to statistics;
Conduct Monte Carlo simulation and compute Monte Carlo standard errors;
Quantify model uncertainties with the bootstrap and Markov chain Monte Carlo;
Demonstrate how emulation addresses the trade-off between model complexity and the ability to quantify uncertainties.
Evaluate different approaches to emulation based on problem characteristics.

Learning Objectives
At the end of this part, readers will be able to:

Distinguish between block maxima and peaks-over-threshold approaches to extreme value analysis;
Apply statistical methods to quantify uncertainty in extremes and return levels;
Select model structures using appropriate statistical methods.
